{
  "doc_id": "prion_0555",
  "text": "A 70-year-old man developed a syndrome of progressive nondominant parietal and occipital dysfunction including palinopsia and a visual field defect.\nDespite the marked focality of his clinical findings, radiologic studies were normal.\nMyoclonus and ataxia began 6 weeks after onset of his illness at which time brain biopsy confirmed Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD).\nThis is the first reported case of palinopsia due to CJD.",
